        "assistant": "Acknowledged — I've read the canonical definition you provided:\n\n> \"Gradient descent is a first-order iterative optimization algorithm that minimizes a differentiable function by repeatedly stepping in the direction of the negative gradient at the current point, with step size controlled by a learning rate.\"\n\nIt's a concise and accurate formulation. It aligns with the explanation I gave, just stated more formally. A few things worth noting about it:\n\n- **\"First-order\"** is a key technical detail — it means the algorithm only uses first derivatives (gradients), not second derivatives (Hessians, as in Newton's method).\n- **\"Differentiable function\"** is an important precondition — the function must have a well-defined gradient everywhere it's evaluated.\n- **\"Iterative\"** captures the repeated-update nature of the process.\n\nLet me know if you'd like to go deeper into any aspect — for example, convergence guarantees, the role of convexity, or how it connects to variants like SGD.",
