        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from simulated annealing?",
        "assistant": "# Gradient Descent vs. Simulated Annealing\n\nThese two algorithms approach optimization from fundamentally different philosophies. Gradient descent is a **deterministic, local, gradient-based** method, while simulated annealing is a **stochastic, global, gradient-free** method inspired by physics.\n\n## The Core Difference\n\n- **Gradient descent** uses calculus — it follows the slope of a differentiable function downhill.\n- **Simulated annealing** uses randomness — it explores the space by random proposals, sometimes *accepting worse solutions* to escape local minima.\n\n## How Simulated Annealing Works\n\nInspired by **metallurgy**: when metal is heated and slowly cooled, atoms settle into low-energy crystalline structures. The algorithm mimics this:\n\n1. **Start** at some point with a high \"temperature\" T.\n2. **Propose** a random nearby candidate point.\n3. **Evaluate** the change in objective: Δf = f(new) − f(current).\n4. **Accept or reject:**\n   - If Δf < 0 (better) → always accept.\n   - If Δf ≥ 0 (worse) → accept with probability $P = e^{-\\Delta f / T}$.\n5. **Cool down**: gradually decrease T according to a schedule.\n6. **Repeat** until T is near zero or budget exhausted.\n\nThe key insight: at high T, the algorithm readily accepts worse moves (broad exploration); at low T, it becomes increasingly greedy (fine-grained exploitation).\n\n## Side-by-Side Comparison\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Type** | Deterministic | Stochastic |\n| **Information used** | Gradient ∇f | Function values f only |\n| **Requires differentiability?** | Yes | No |\n| **Search style** | Local, follows slope | Global, random exploration |\n| **Accepts worse moves?** | Never | Yes, probabilistically |\n| **Escapes local minima?** | No (gets stuck) | Yes (by design) |\n| **Convergence guarantee** | To local min (convex → global) | To global min (with proper cooling, in the limit) |\n| **Speed in practice** | Fast | Slow |\n| **Hyperparameters** | Learning rate | Initial T, cooling schedule, neighbor function |\n| **Works on discrete spaces?** | No | Yes |\n| **Scales to millions of parameters?** | Yes | Poorly |\n\n## Intuition: Hill Descent vs. Drunken Walk\n\n- **Gradient descent**: A careful hiker in fog who always steps in the steepest downhill direction. Reliably finds *a* valley — but possibly the wrong one.\n- **Simulated annealing**: A hiker who starts out drunk, willing to climb over ridges to explore other valleys. As they sober up (cool down), they settle into the deepest valley they can find.\n\n## What Each Is Good At\n\n**Gradient descent excels when:**\n- The function is differentiable and reasonably smooth.\n- You have many parameters (high dimensions).\n- The landscape is convex or \"benign\" (deep learning landscapes often are, in practice).\n- You need speed.\n\n**Simulated annealing excels when:**\n- The function is **non-differentiable**, **discrete**, or **black-box** (no gradient available).\n- The landscape is **rugged with many local optima**.\n- The problem is **combinatorial** — e.g., the **Traveling Salesman Problem**, scheduling, circuit design, protein folding.\n- You need a **global minimum** more than speed.\n\n## Acceptance Probability — The Heart of SA\n\nThe Metropolis criterion $P = e^{-\\Delta f / T}$ has elegant properties:\n\n| Temperature | Behavior |\n|---|---|\n| **T → ∞** | Accepts almost any move → pure random search |\n| **T moderate** | Mix of exploration and exploitation |\n| **T → 0** | Only accepts improvements → behaves like greedy hill climbing |\n\nThe **cooling schedule** (how T decreases over time) is critical. Common choices:\n- Linear: $T_k = T_0 - k\\Delta$\n- Geometric: $T_k = T_0 \\cdot \\alpha^k$ with $\\alpha \\in (0.8, 0.99)$\n- Logarithmic: $T_k = T_0 / \\log(k+1)$ — slow but has theoretical convergence guarantees\n\n## Convergence Guarantees\n\n- **Gradient descent**: With proper learning rate, converges to a **local** minimum (global if convex). Fast.\n- **Simulated annealing**: With a sufficiently slow cooling schedule (e.g., logarithmic), converges to the **global** minimum *with probability 1* — but possibly very slowly.\n\nThe catch: the theoretical schedule is so slow that in practice, SA gives no guarantees — but it works remarkably well empirically.\n\n## A Concrete Example\n\nConsider minimizing a function like:\n\n$$f(x) = x^2 + 10\\sin(5x)$$\n\nThis has many local minima inside a global parabolic shape.\n\n- **Gradient descent**: Will roll into whichever local well it starts nearest. Trapped.\n- **Simulated annealing**: Will jump between wells early on, gradually settling into the global minimum as it cools.\n\n## Hybrid Approaches\n\nThe two paradigms aren't mutually exclusive:\n- **Basin hopping**: Combines random perturbation (SA-like) with gradient-based local minimization at each step.\n- **Stochastic Gradient Langevin Dynamics (SGLD)**: Adds Gaussian noise to gradient updates — a sort of annealed gradient descent.\n- **Genetic algorithms with local search**: Use evolutionary global search plus gradient-based refinement.\n\n## Connection to the Canonical Definition\n\nRecall: gradient descent is a \"first-order iterative optimization algorithm that minimizes a differentiable function by repeatedly stepping in the direction of the negative gradient.\" Two phrases in that definition mark the contrast sharply:\n\n- **\"Differentiable function\"** — SA imposes no such requirement; it works on any function you can evaluate, including discrete or black-box objectives.\n- **\"Direction of the negative gradient\"** — SA has no notion of direction; it proposes random neighbors and uses *acceptance probability* rather than directional information.\n\nIn short: gradient descent exploits structure (the gradient) for efficient local descent; simulated annealing sacrifices that efficiency to gain robustness against rugged, non-smooth, or non-differentiable landscapes.\n\nWant me to walk through a numerical SA example, or compare it to other gradient-free methods like genetic algorithms or Bayesian optimization?",
